The paper deals with a memory allocation problem that can be modeled as a version of bin packing, which is a classic problem in computer science. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also discusses approximation algorithms and NP-hardness proofs, which are common topics in the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.AL (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. The paper also mentions online algorithms, which are studied in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the more general case where each bin may contain at most k parts of items, which is related to the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category.
